REFTEXT: Electro-Optical Dazzler inflicts a penalty of 10% ECM on all guided missiles targeting the host ground unit.
This units is full of electronic device to detect or scramble enemy electronic devices.
AIRLIFT units can be transported by helicopters featuring the AIRLIFTER trait.
This vehicle is designed to tow heavy equipment on the battlefield. Prime movers can range from heavy trucks to artillery tractors.
This unit is equipped with radio direction-finding systems. Enemy radio signals are intercepted and used to triangulate the approximate position of the enemy unit.

Anti-Air (AA) guns are weapons designed to take out fast-moving airborne targets.\nThese types of guns are frequently emplaced in quick traversing turrets with a high rate of fire and elevation. In this way, with more advanced systems using targeting computers and radar, they can track and shoot at aircraft and helicopters at a moment’s notice. AA guns are often found in dual or even quadruple mounts. In addition, these guns are frequently used for great effect in a direct-fire role against lightly armored ground targets.
False Flag units are infiltration units dressed in civilian clothes, or even enemy uniforms, breaking military laws.

A Gatling gun is a multi-barrelled automatic rotary cannon capable of shooting a massive quantity of rounds extremely fast.\nUsing an electronic firing mechanism, a modern Gatling gun (also known as minigun) can fire so quickly it is in danger of running out of ammunition within seconds. Gatling guns are often cumbersome weapons and are relegated to be used on aircraft or stable land platforms. They can be employed as a close-in defensive system to saturate a target area by throwing a hail of fire, an anti-aircraft gun, or even an airborne anti-tank weapon able to punch through the weak top plating of many armored vehicles.
Although UAV doesn't have ECM, they are very hard to target effectively by enemy fire. Also, the operator being safe on the ground, an UAV doesn't suffer from stress nor evacuate automatically.
This unit represents an army's crème de la crème: highly trained professionals, well-equipped and with more combat experience than regular troops.

A missile fired from a land platform at another land target, skimming just above the ground during its flight.\nMany ground-to-ground missiles find their origin in their airborne brethren, featuring a similar array of propulsion and targeting methods. A distinct subset are anti-tank guided missiles (ATGMs). These are crew-served weapons, fired at enemy ground units and can be controlled in flight. ATGMs can be found as secondary or even primary armament on a wide variety of vehicles, from dedicated carriers to infantry fighting vehicles and helicopters.
Leader units grant +1 veterancy level to all nearby units.
Sniper units gain a +500% damage bonus, +1 Stealth level and Accuracy bonus when not moving. The sniper must remain still for 10 seconds.

An unguided or “dumb” bomb is an explosive employed by aircraft or helicopters against enemy ground units.\nSimple and destructive, unguided bombs are also known as gravity bombs. A disadvantage is that bombs dropped as a payload need to have the user fly over a target, and a rather inaccurate. Unguided bombs can come in many shapes and sizes, from small bomblets to bunker busters targeting hardened targets.
Main Battle Tank. The tank is a heavily multirole armored vehicle, effective against any type of ground vehicle, as well as infantry.

This unit is made of part-time soldiers, such as hastily called-up reservists, former police, or irregular militia. While not cowards, with less training and older equipment, they should be considered second-rate troops.
Prime movers, just like regular transport, can carry infantry units, but move heavy guns in tow.

A grenade launcher can lob grenades across short distances.\nA grenade launcher solves one of the major issues of using handheld explosives by increasing the range. Some launchers are stand alone semi- or fully automatic, being able to saturate an area. Others are single-shot but can be attached to weapons, such as assault rifles. Many armored fighting vehicles feature fixed grenade launchers as a defensive weapon or to provide masking smoke screens.
Laser Designator units grant an accuracy bonus to Guided Munitions while the target is within line of sight.
Artillery howitzer takes time to prepare and fire, but it can shoot at a very high distance while remaining perfectly accurate.
Units specialized in anti-aircraft combat, i.e. against both helicopters and aircraft.

A Gatling gun is a multi-barrelled automatic rotary cannon capable of shooting a massive quantity of rounds extremely fast.\nUsing an electronic firing mechanism, a modern Gatling gun (also known as minigun) can fire so quickly it is in danger of running out of ammunition within seconds. Gatling guns are often cumbersome weapons and are relegated to be used on aircraft or stable land platforms. They can be employed as a close-in defensive system to saturate a target area by throwing a hail of fire, an anti-aircraft gun, or even an airborne anti-tank weapon able to punch through the weak top plating of many armored vehicles.
Guided Munitions can be bombs or shells, fired directly or indirectly, receiving an accuracy bonus on laser-designated targets.
False Flag units are easily mistaken with friendly or neutral ones. In combat, the threat level is lower than any other unit, meaning they'll always be targeted last.
Units whose primary mission is to transport squads of infantry and unload them on the battlefield.\nThese units can be sent back to the rear once the infantry has unloaded.
This vehicle is designed to move infantry units on the battlefield. Transports can range from fast jeeps and trucks to even helicopters.

A flamethrower is a destructive weapon projecting a controllable jet of flames. Using liquid fuels or other incendiary mixtures such as napalm, flamethrowers can be vehicle-mounted or man-portable. \n\nAlthough they have a very short range, flamethrowers are highly effective against infantry, even behind cover.

A medium machine gun is a crew-served infantry weapon capable of automatic fire at intermediate ranges.\This type of belt-fed machine gun is light enough to be transported by individual soldiers, but most often needs a small crew to be operated effectively. Medium machine guns fire, almost in all cases, 5,56mm (NATO) or 7.62mm (Warsaw Pact) rounds, which can also be used in other small arms. Medium machine guns are frequently featured as primary weapons on soft-skinned and lightly armed vehicles or as coaxial armament in heavier units.
Ground Surveillance Radar units receive a +1 Optics level (Very Good to Exceptional) when not moving.
This recon unit is equipped with a portable Ground Surveillance Radar, detecting targets beyond visual range. Once deployed, it needs to remain stationary to function.

EW planes have very high ECM which they project in the area-of-effect, scrambling any radar SAM's targeting system by the same value. It also has SEAD optics, meaning it will spot SAM radar from afar.
Recon units can deploy further ahead, but only during the initial deployment phase.

This unit excels in reconnaissance, gathering intelligence, and spotting targets on the battlefield. Recon troops are light units, masters in moving quickly on the battlefield and observing enemy units undetected.
This second-line infantry unit is only lightly equipped for combat, tasked instead with patrolling and securing the rear. These soldiers guard against enemy saboteurs and infiltration attempts.
AIRLIFTER helicopters can transport light vehicles and equipment with the AIRLIFT trait.
This unit is equipped with an Electro-Optical Dazzler. This is an active protection system designed to disrupt the guidance of incoming anti-tank guided missiles.
Shock units inflict more suppression when fighting at close combat ranges, including woods and urban terrain.

Each level of optics is indicated to the left of the unit name:
#RECO1: good
#RECO2: very good
#RECO3: exceptional

An unguided or “dumb” bomb is an explosive employed by aircraft or helicopters against enemy ground units.\nSimple and destructive, unguided bombs are also known as gravity bombs. A disadvantage is that bombs dropped as a payload need to have the user fly over a target, and a rather inaccurate. Unguided bombs can come in many shapes and sizes, from small bomblets to bunker busters targeting hardened targets.

The standard weapon for a large number of frontline soldiers, the battle rifle is effective against enemy troops at intermediate ranges.\nHeavy and powerful, battle rifles are very accurate and deadly when the shooter is immobile, but quite less than an assault rifle on the move, especially since it uses smaller magazines. Most assault rifles can be modified with accessories such as scopes, foregrips, night vision devices, or single-shot grenade launchers.

A RECOILLESS RIFLE is a shoulder-fired or crew served weapon designed to provide fire-support. It can engage armored targets or infantry.\nThese launchers fire an unguided rocket-propelled anti-tank projectile, giving the regular combat soldier an efficient, portable weapon to neutralize enemy tanks or infantry. They are short-range weapons, best used in ambushes or from cover such as buildings or forests.
Half-sized infantry squad. A reduced complement numbering 5-6 soldiers.
Special Forces units take less suppression in combat and deal more damage - on top of the Elite veterancy level.

Unguided air-to-ground rockets are fired from aircraft and helicopters at ground targets.\nA common weapon, rockets normally lack an active guidance system, separating them from missiles. A simple and easy-to-use weapon - though not very accurate - rockets are convenient in a short-range or area saturation role. Carrying various types of warheads, rockets are frequently fired from rocket pods in devastating salvoes.

A small, hand-held explosive that can be thrown by an individual soldier.\nGrenades can be encountered in many shapes and sizes, including fragmentation anti-personal, smoke grenades, gas, or even anti-tank grenades. As extremely close-range weapons, they are used in various combat situations, including clearing houses or bunkers, thrown into vehicles, or as boobytraps. Due to proximity and sometimes large blast radius, grenades are often equally dangerous to the user as to the enemy.

This is an indicator to place the cost of the unit within its category.

The indicator #pi3{blue} indicates that the unit is in the top 25% of prices.

Indicator #pi2{green} indicates that the unit is in the second highest price range.

Indicator #pi1{orange} indicates that the unit is below the median price, in the third quarter of prices.

Indicator #score_05{red} indicates that the unit is in the lowest price quarter.

Howitzers occupy in name a specific niche as an artillery gun, historically firing shells at lower velocity but at higher elevation.\nOver the years, the distinction between howitzers and regular artillery guns has merged, with both types of guns now featuring longer barrels, extended ranges, extra propellant charges, and higher elevations. Many modern artillery systems, including self-propelled ones, now carry the label howitzer.

Bombardement. Bombing runs can be carried out with a variety of guided or unguided bombs. The type of bomb can vary from the simple bomb with blast and fragmentation damage, to cluster bombs or even napalm.
Recon units have excellent optics and stealth abilities. This allows them to scout the battlefield and spot enemy targets.
Includes any unit that is not specialized in a specific type of combat.
Line infantry can be considered classic soldiers, without any specialization.
Units dedicated to replenish ammo and fuel. They can also perform repairs.
Infantry squad (around 10 soldiers) multirole (long range combat, short range combat) and with weapons against armor if necessary.

SIGINT units will automatically detect enemy units within two separate detection ranges, even when lacking line of sight. A different label is shown depending on the range without revealing the type or exact location of the enemy unit. \n\nSIGINT units cannot detect enemy units featuring the Special Forces or False Flag trait.
This unit is equipped with advanced laser designating devices. This allows operators to “paint” targets within their field of view, which then can be hit by laser-guided precision munitions.
Jammer units will downgrade the optics of any enemy recon unit with the radar, as well as cancel artillery correction, within its area of effect.
Infantry weapons team. This is a small team, usually 2-4 soldiers, operating specialized weapons.
Transport units can carry infantry squads, groups, or teams.
Rocket artillery system with low accuracy, but able to saturate a large target area with a massive volume of firepower.

Heavy machine guns are potent crew-served weapons and can be used against land and air targets.\nThese types of belt-fed machine guns are often less mobile than their lighter counterparts, and need to be fired from a stable platform, such as a heavy-duty tripod, vehicle, or aircraft. Frequently operated by small teams of soldiers, heavy machine guns fire large-caliber rounds (typically 12.7mm or 14.5mm) capable of inflicting destructive damage. Even when fired at armored targets, heavy machine guns can neutralize key equipment such as optic systems or radio antennas, resulting in a mission kill.

[SHOCK#trait_SHOCK]: Generates suppression to any infantry unit that does not have the [SHOCK] ability.\n[PARA#trait_PARA]: the unit can be deployed forward\n[SML#trait_SML]: the section has less than 6 soldiers
Unsteady units take more suppression in combat.

Unguided air-to-ground rockets are fired from aircraft and helicopters at ground targets.\nA common weapon, rockets normally lack an active guidance system, separating them from missiles. A simple and easy-to-use weapon - though not very accurate - rockets are convenient in a short-range or area saturation role. Carrying various types of warheads, rockets are frequently fired from rocket pods in devastating salvoes.
Tanks with ERA applied have increased their maximum damage (hit points) to represent their better resilience to HEAT damage.
Infantry squad. A full complement numbers usually around 12 soldiers.

A special type of missile designed to home automatically in on and destroy enemy radar systems.\nThese kinds of missiles, also known as ARM, can be used against not only ground-based radar, but also communication equipment, jamming stations, and other radio emission sources. Radiation missiles are commonly employed by specialist Suppression of Enemy Air Defenses (SEAD) aircraft to neutralize air defense systems by destroying their active radar.
This vehicle is equipped with defensive smoke launchers. They can deploy a smoke screen that temporarily masks the unit.

Each level of optics is indicated to the left of the unit name:
#RECO1: good
#RECO2: very good
#RECO3: exceptional
Amphibious vehicles can enter and cross waters at 1/3 of their normal (offroad) speed.

A missile fired at ground targets from aircraft or helicopters.\nAir-to-ground missiles feature a large variety of propulsion and guidance systems, such as laser designation, infrared, optical, or satellite. Much like their air-to-air missile cousins, ground attack missiles can feature longer-range but slower jet engines or short-range, high-speed rocket motors with a considerable crossover between types and missions. Some are guided, such as anti-tank guided missiles, while others are fire-and-forget, allowing aircraft to fall back after engaging the enemy from a safe distance.
This vehicle is designed to operate both on land and water. Thanks to their waterproof hulls and dedicated propulsion, such as water jets or propellers, they can slowly cross bodies of water.

Sniper rifles can hit targets at longer range than regular assault rifles thanks to a scope. It can only be fire while stationnary, with a low rate of fire, but is very accurate, deadly and will cause a large amount of stress to the target unit.
Units specialized in capturing or contesting enemy-controlled areas.

Unguided air-to-ground rockets are fired from aircraft and helicopters at ground targets.\nA common weapon, rockets normally lack an active guidance system, separating them from missiles. A simple and easy-to-use weapon - though not very accurate - rockets are convenient in a short-range or area saturation role. Carrying various types of warheads, rockets are frequently fired from rocket pods in devastating salvoes.

Howitzers occupy in name a specific niche as an artillery gun, historically firing shells at lower velocity but at higher elevation.\nOver the years, the distinction between howitzers and regular artillery guns has merged, with both types of guns now featuring longer barrels, extended ranges, extra propellant charges, and higher elevations. Many modern artillery systems, including self-propelled ones, now carry the label howitzer.

This headquarters unit does not only feature commanders but also critical command-and-control equipment, including radio and other communication devices. This allows for more effective tactical leadership on the battlefield.

This unit contains highly trained sharpshooters who excel in infiltration tactics, camouflage, and reconnaissance. Equipped with powerful scoped sniper rifles, these specialist soldiers can engage targets at long ranges without being seen.

A rocket is an unguided warhead-equipped projectile powered by a rocket engine. Amongst other things, it differs from missiles by the lack of active guidance systems.\n\nArtillery units equipped with rockets compensate for a lack of accuracy with the ability to quickly saturate and destroy an area with a large number of rockets.
Fire Direction units reduce the aim time of nearby artillery units on top of granting +1 Veterancy level.
Aircraft specialized in the anti-radar warfare, i.e. the search and destruction of enemy air defense units equipped with radar.

A Gatling gun is a multi-barrelled automatic rotary cannon capable of shooting a massive quantity of rounds extremely fast.\nUsing an electronic firing mechanism, a modern Gatling gun (also known as minigun) can fire so quickly it is in danger of running out of ammunition within seconds. Gatling guns are often cumbersome weapons and are relegated to be used on aircraft or stable land platforms. They can be employed as a close-in defensive system to saturate a target area by throwing a hail of fire, an anti-aircraft gun, or even an airborne anti-tank weapon able to punch through the weak top plating of many armored vehicles.
This large helicopter is capable of lifting heavy cargo, vehicles, or towed guns. This can be done either inside the fuselage or slung underneath.

Unguided air-to-ground rockets are fired from aircraft and helicopters at ground targets.\nA common weapon, rockets normally lack an active guidance system, separating them from missiles. A simple and easy-to-use weapon - though not very accurate - rockets are convenient in a short-range or area saturation role. Carrying various types of warheads, rockets are frequently fired from rocket pods in devastating salvoes.
Airborne units can deploy further ahead, using Forward Deployment, but only during the initial deployment phase.
Explosive reactive armor (ERA) is intended to counteract HEAT antitank munitions and provides a boost in the survivability of the tank and its crew.
Infantry squad (around 10 soldiers) specialized in close range combat and in urban / building environment

An incendiary rocket launcher is a specialized weapon capable of firing thermal warheads at land targets.\nThe warhead of this rocket is often confused for napalm, but the incendiary rocket launcher in many ways better resembles a stand-off flamethrower, capable of burning fortified structures such as bunkers from a distance. This launcher can be fired by a single soldier and is effective at land fortifications, buildings, and enemy squads.
Infantry assault squads specialized in short-range combat, in particular in urban combat.
Security units increase their Optics and identification levels to Good when not moving, similar to Recon units, although they remain an Infantry squad.
Armored vehicle designed to carry infantry into battle and provide direct-fire support. The IFV usually carries effective weapons against infantry and other armored vehicles.

This unit is composed of soldiers who are highly motivated, well-drilled, or politically indoctrinated. Going into battle with plenty of enthusiasm, these eager troops will endure even the hardest battlefield conditions in stride.

This unit is an Unmanned Aerial Vehicle, a drone piloted from a the ground by an operator and used for reconnaissance. Small, slow & silent, it is hard to spot by the human eye and intended to be discarded as a bird by radars.
This unit features the oft-detested military police. As law enforcement, they ensure order behind the lines and instill harsh discipline within the army’s ranks.

A missile fired at ground targets from aircraft or helicopters.\nAir-to-ground missiles feature a large variety of propulsion and guidance systems, such as laser designation, infrared, optical, or satellite. Much like their air-to-air missile cousins, ground attack missiles can feature longer-range but slower jet engines or short-range, high-speed rocket motors with a considerable crossover between types and missions. Some are guided, such as anti-tank guided missiles, while others are fire-and-forget, allowing aircraft to fall back after engaging the enemy from a safe distance.
Air-dropped explosive weapon that ejects small unguided cluster bombs.

A submachine gun is a quick-firing, short-range firearm.\nSubmachine guns (SMGs) fire smaller cartridges, most often used in handguns, which allows for a more compact and easier to wield automatic weapon. This also means their stopping power and range are less than a heavier assault rifle. Rear-echelon troops or vehicle crews frequently field submachine guns as a personal defense weapon.

A fast-flying missile launched from an aircraft or helicopter for the purpose of destroying airborne targets.\nAir-to-air missiles can be broadly divided into two categories: those designed to engage hostile aircraft at very short range, also known as within visual range missiles; and those that fly far and neutralize targets beyond visual range. Short-range missiles frequently feature rapid rocket motors and heat-seeking guidance systems. Long-range missiles often use slower jet engines and radar guidance to engage hostile aircraft across considerable distances.
This unit is an Unmanned Aerial Vehicle, or drone, piloted remotely. UAVs provide critical battlefield surveillance and fly reconnaissance missions.
This unit is composed of soldiers trained for combat with Infantry Fighting Vehicles, and fight side by side once dismounted. This follows common mechanized infantry doctrine.

Mortars are indirect-fire crew-served infantry weapons capable of lobbing shells in high trajectories across medium distances.\nMortars come in various calibers, from 50mm to 120mm to the occasional massive 240mm. Caliber size determines their range, how easily they can be transported, rate of fire, and destructive power. Some larger units are vehicle-mounted on dedicated carriers, allowing quick displacement after shooting. Capable of firing off different types of rounds, from high-explosive to smoke or illumination, mortars provide indispensable organic fire support on the battlefield.
Armored vehicles feature effective armor plating against weapons up to 20mm in caliber.

An Laser Guided Bomb (LGB) is an explosive employed by aircraft against enemy ground units.\nSimple and destructive, guided bombs are also known as GBU(Guided Bomb Unit). A disadvantage is that bombs dropped as a payload need to have the user fly over a target, but are rather accurate. Guided bombs can come in many shapes and sizes.
Units equipped with Smoke Launchers can create a single-use smoke screen by pressing B or SMOKE in the order panel.
UAVs are aerial units completely immune to suppression.

An autocannon is an automatic gun capable of rapidly firing medium-sized caliber rounds.\nThis kind of weapon can attack light armored and soft-skinned vehicles, including helicopters, and is deadly effective against uncovered enemy soldiers. Most autocannons feature calibers between 20mm to 40mm and can be equipped with armor-piercing (AP) or high-explosive (HE) cartridges. Several types of armored personnel carriers and infantry fighting vehicles carry an autocannon as their primary armament.
Military Police units grant a suppression regeneration bonus and remove any Unsteady traits of nearby units.
Infantry half squad (around 5 soldiers) specialized in close range combat and in urban / building environment
This light vehicle or towed gun is designed to be airlifted by large helicopters as part of tactical air assault operations.

A surface-to-air missile (SAM) is fired from the ground against airborne targets.\nMuch like other missiles, a SAM can feature different propulsion and guidance methods, from infrared to radar-homing. Man-portable air-defense systems (MANPADs) are short-range SAM missiles that can be used by a single soldier against low-flying helicopters and attack aircraft. Medium-range variants are often installed on a single self-contained vehicle platform. Long-range heavier SAMs are at times part of complex sets of vehicles, with separate radar and command units. Throwing up a protective umbrella for friendly land forces, surface-to-air missiles can be deadly effective against enemy aircraft across a variety of distances.
Aircraft specialized in electronic warfare. Loaded with counter-measures, it flies over enemy territory to locate enemy SAM's radar emissions and scramble them.

This unit is armed with precision-guided munitions, such as Laser-Guided Bombs (LGBs) or Cannon-Launched Guided Projectiles (CLGPs). Highly accurate, these ranged weapons can be guided onto a target with a laser designator.
Mortars are the most responsive indirect-fire weapons.\nWhile they are capable of engaging targets quickly, mortars do not have great range and quickly become inaccurate.
Recon units have excellent optics and stealth abilities. This allows them to scout the battlefield and spot enemy targets.
IFV Infantry units take less suppression in combat when near an Infantry Fighting Vehicle.
This specialized leader unit is equipped with fire-control systems, sensors, communication devices, and other equipment to improve the indirect fire of subordinate artillery guns.
Main Battle Tank. The tank is a heavily multirole armored vehicle, effective against any type of ground vehicle, as well as infantry.

A tank gun is a large-caliber, high-velocity gun capable of firing various projectiles against a variety of targets.\nA tank gun is the primary means of engaging other tanks or armored vehicles with direct fire. Featuring different calibers, between 90mm to 125mm, a tank gun is often emplaced in a turret, creating a flexible yet hard-hitting weapon. When assisted by advanced targeting computers and sights, a tank gun can engage almost any kind of unit, even airborne targets, regardless of the weather or time of day. A tank gun fires off a variety of different shells, at times supported by an autoloader, including armor-piercing kinetic (AP), armor-piercing, fin-stabilized, discarding sabot (APFSDS), high-explosive (HE), or high-explosive anti-tank (HEAT). Some guns can even fire specially adapted guided missiles.

The standard weapon for the vast majority of combat soldiers, the assault rifle is effective against enemy troops at intermediate ranges.\nAn assault rifle can be select-fire, with semi-automatic being more accurate, while full automatic best used in close range fighting. Carbines are shortened assault rifles, and over the years, two distinct groups of rounds have been developed: lighter 5.56mm or full power 7.62mm cartridges. Most assault rifles can be modified with accessories such as scopes, foregrips, night vision devices, or single-shot grenade launchers.

An Anti-Tank Rocket Launcher is a shoulder-fired weapon designed to take out armored or reinforced land targets.\nThese launchers fire an unguided rocket-propelled anti-tank projectile, giving the regular combat soldier an efficient, portable weapon to neutralize enemy tanks or vehicles. They are short-range weapons, best used in ambushes or from cover such as buildings or forests.
Units designed specifically to engage and destroy enemy tanks, often with limited operational capacities.
This unit is trained to be inserted onto the battlefield through the air. Highly mobile but lightly equipped, airborne troops can rapidly deploy ahead of the regular army.
Resolute units take less suppression in combat.

Mortars are indirect-fire crew-served infantry weapons capable of lobbing shells in high trajectories across medium distances.\nMortars come in various calibers, from 50mm to 120mm to the occasional massive 240mm. Caliber size determines their range, how easily they can be transported, rate of fire, and destructive power. Some larger units are vehicle-mounted on dedicated carriers, allowing quick displacement after shooting. Capable of firing off different types of rounds, from high-explosive to smoke or illumination, mortars provide indispensable organic fire support on the battlefield.
Infantry half squad (around 5 soldiers) multirole (long range combat, short range combat) and with weapons against armor if necessary.
This unit features hardened soldiers specifically trained and equipped for close-quarter battles, assault operations, and hand-to-hand combat.

A medium machine gun is a crew-served infantry weapon capable of automatic fire at intermediate ranges.\This type of belt-fed machine gun is light enough to be transported by individual soldiers, but most often needs a small crew to be operated effectively. Medium machine guns fire, almost in all cases, 5,56mm (NATO) or 7.62mm (Warsaw Pact) rounds, which can also be used in other small arms. Medium machine guns are frequently featured as primary weapons on soft-skinned and lightly armed vehicles or as coaxial armament in heavier units.
